Reasoning plays a big part in math since I use it every single day in doing my homework.  Thinking is also a key skill in reading and writing. Notice that we are trying to find a region whose area we can compare with the given large square's area.  By the Pythagorean Theorem, the side length of the small square is \[\sqrt{(2-1)^2+(3-2)^2}= \sqrt{1+1}=\sqrt{2}\] units long.  To find the area of the given square, we square the side length, so the area is \[\textcolor{#c00}{(\sqrt{2}\cdot\sqrt{2})^2=4}\] square units.  To find the area of the small shaded square, we run the same process in reverse since the side length is also unknown.  We square both sides of the equation to get \[9=x^2,\] where \[x\] represents the side length of the small square.  Then \[\textcolor{#0a0}{x^2=9}\] and thus \[x=3.\]  To find the area of the small square, we square \[x,\] so it is \[\textcolor{magenta}{9}\] square units.  In ratio form, the small shaded square to the large shaded square (counting only the shaded regions) is \[9:4.\]  Now let's move on to the big square.  Using the Pythagorean Theorem (since all the sides of this square are equal) we compute \[\sqrt{(1-2)^{2}+(0-3)^{2}}=\sqrt{10}.\]  Thus the area of the large square is \[\textcolor{#c00}{(\sqrt{10}\cdot\sqrt{10})^2=10}\] square units.  We see that there are \[n=\frac{9}{4}\] shaded squares and \[m=\frac{10}{1}\] large squares.  Simplifying \[n\div m=\frac{9}{4}\div \frac{10}{1} =\frac{9}{4}\cdot \frac{1}{10} =\boxed{\frac{9}{40}}.\]\end{asy}
