To solve this problem, we need to determine the year when the number of wrens is less than 10% of the original number, given that the population decreases by 40% each year. This means that each year, the population is 60% of the previous year's population. We can represent this as a geometric sequence where the common ratio is 0.6.

Let $N_0$ be the number of wrens on June 1, 2004. Then, the number of wrens on June 1 in the $n^\text{th}$ year after 2004 is given by $N_n = N_0 \times (0.6)^n$. We want to find the smallest positive integer $n$ such that $N_n < 0.1N_0$.

\begin{align*}
N_n &< 0.1N_0 \\
N_0 \times (0.6)^n &< 0.1N_0 \\
(0.6)^n &< 0.1
\end{align*}

Taking the logarithm of both sides:

\begin{align*}
\log(0.6)^n &< \log(0.1) \\
n \log(0.6) &< \log(0.1) \\
n &> \frac{\log(0.1)}{\log(0.6)}
\end{align*}

Using a calculator, we find that:

\begin{align*}
n &> \frac{\log(0.1)}{\log(0.6)} \\
n &> \frac{-1}{0.2217}
\end{align*}

Since $n$ must be a positive integer, we take the ceiling of the right-hand side:

\begin{align*}
n &> 4.504
\end{align*}

Therefore, $n = 5$. This means that the number of wrens will be less than 10% of the original number in the 5th year after 2004, which is $\boxed{2009}$.

